---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../components/SiteFooter.astro';
import SideNav from '../components/SideNav.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Portfolio">
  <SiteHeader />
  <SideNav />
  <main class="portfolio-main">
    <h1 class="portfolio-title">Portfolio</h1>

    <section class="project-section">

      <h2 class="project-heading">Cookie cutter</h2>

      <div class="project-row">

        <div class="desc-col">
          <div class="project-box">
            <p>Cookies, stored by websites in your browser, and their contents are often deliberately scrambled so you can't tell what's being tracked. I built a browser extension that unscrambles and explains a site's cookies in plain language, and runs the entire analysis on your own device, so no cookie value is ever sent anywhere. This not only helps breakdown exactly what data is being shared and with whom, it also gives you the option to filter them to protect your data.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="project-box project-box--indent">
            <p>The demo lets you set how cookies are blocked, add trusted sites to an allowlist, and see quick stats on active, changed, and blocked cookies. The main list shows every cookie on the page with its category, a colour-coded risk rating, and its purpose — click one to see a plain-language explanation and its raw value. Below that, a live log tracks blocked cookie traffic, with buttons to refresh, clear the log, or open options.</p>
          </div>

          <img class="demo-arrow" src="/images/portfolio/pink-arrow.png" alt="" aria-hidden="true" />
        </div>

        <div class="demo-wrapper">
          <iframe
            class="demo-frame demo-frame--dark"
            src="/demos/cookie-guard-dark.html"
            title="Cookie Guard Reporter — interactive demo (dark)"
            loading="lazy"
            sandbox="allow-scripts allow-same-origin"
          ></iframe>
          <iframe
            class="demo-frame demo-frame--light"
            src="/demos/cookie-guard-light.html"
            title="Cookie Guard Reporter — interactive demo (light)"
            loading="lazy"
            sandbox="allow-scripts allow-same-origin"
          ></iframe>
        </div>

      </div>

      <div class="project-box project-box--right">
        <p class="how-title">How does it do this?</p>
        <ul class="how-list">
          <li><strong>Fully offline</strong> — every cookie value is decoded and analysed locally in the browser; nothing is ever transmitted to an external service.</li>
          <li><strong>Multi-layer decoder</strong> — recognises and peels back up to four layers of encoding (URL, Base64, hexadecimal, JWT, and JSON, plus detection of binary Protocol Buffers data), since real tracking cookies are frequently wrapped several times over.</li>
          <li><strong>Content classifier</strong> — reads the decoded data for tell-tale signals like identifiers, analytics tags, and timestamps to sort each cookie into a category (functional, analytics, advertising) and assign a privacy-risk rating.</li>
          <li><strong>Known-tracker knowledge base</strong> — instantly recognises common trackers such as Google Analytics (_ga) and Meta (_fbp) and explains what they do.</li>
          <li><strong>Plain-language output</strong> — turns the whole analysis into a readable summary anyone can understand, while staying fast and private by capping values at 4,096 characters and limiting decoding to four passes.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </section>

    <section class="project-section">

      <h2 class="project-heading">SSH Brute-Force Intrusion Detection System</h2>

      <div class="ssh-row">

        <div class="ssh-images">
          <img class="ssh-img ssh-img--attack ssh-img--dark" src="/images/portfolio/attack_defense_dark.png" alt="Diagram: SSH brute-force attack and how detector.py defends against it" />
          <img class="ssh-img ssh-img--attack ssh-img--light" src="/images/portfolio/attack_defense_light.png" alt="Diagram: SSH brute-force attack and how detector.py defends against it" />

          <img class="ssh-img ssh-img--dark" src="/images/portfolio/terminal-dark.png" alt="Terminal output from detector.py flagging repeated brute-force attempts" />
          <img class="ssh-img ssh-img--light" src="/images/portfolio/terminal-light.png" alt="Terminal output from detector.py flagging repeated brute-force attempts" />
        </div>

        <div class="ssh-text">

          <div class="project-box">
            <p>Servers are constantly hit by automated attacks that guess passwords thousands of times until one works. I built a Python tool that watches a server's login records as they're written and catches these brute-force attacks in real time, then produces professional-grade alerts that drop straight into a security team's monitoring pipeline.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="project-box">
            <p class="how-title">How does it do this?</p>
            <ul class="how-list">
              <li><strong>Reads logs live</strong> — tails the server's authentication log as it's written, so detection happens in the moment rather than after the fact.</li>
              <li><strong>Sliding-window detection</strong> — for every source address it keeps a rolling 60-second history of failed logins (the same pattern used to spot bursts of fraud), and only raises an alarm when an address crosses five failures inside that window — so a mistyped password never triggers a false alert.</li>
              <li><strong>Structured JSON alerts</strong> — each detection is written out with the severity, the attacker's address, and the targeted account, in a machine-readable format ready for automated tooling.</li>
              <li><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK tagging</strong> — every alert is labelled T1110.001 (Password Guessing) using the industry-standard threat catalogue security teams rely on, so the output needs no translation.</li>
              <li><strong>Validated on a real system</strong> — tested against a live OpenSSH server on an Ubuntu 24.04 virtual machine, with simulated attacks and real logs captured from the system journal.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

        </div>

      </div>

    </section>

    <section class="project-section">

      <h2 class="project-heading">Lynra</h2>

      <div class="lynra-row">

        <div class="lynra-text">

          <div class="project-box">
            <p>Ash dieback is a fungal disease killing ash trees across Ireland and Europe, and treating them by hand at scale isn't practical. As part of a four-person team at the Patch Summer Accelerator, I helped build Lynra: an autonomous rover that identifies ash trees and delivers a lifesaving biostimulant directly into them through a micro-injection, making large-scale treatment possible. We designed, prototyped, and 3D-printed the rover ourselves and presented it live at Demo Day to an audience of 300+ investors, founders, and industry leaders.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="project-box">
            <p class="how-title">How does it do this?</p>
            <ul class="how-list">
              <li><strong>AI tree detection</strong> — a custom object-detection and recognition model in Roboflow identifies the base of ash trees (the injection site) from the rover's camera feed in real time.</li>
              <li><strong>Onboard processing</strong> — the model runs on a Raspberry Pi mounted on the rover, letting it detect and make decisions based on the frames it analyses, which then instruct an Arduino that directly controls the rover's movements.</li>
              <li><strong>Automated micro-injection</strong> — once a target is identified, the rover positions itself and delivers a precise micro-dose of biostimulant into the tree using a needle, without damaging the trunk.</li>
              <li><strong>Custom-built hardware</strong> — the chassis and delivery system were designed in Fusion 360, prototyped, and 3D-printed in-house by the team.</li>
              <li><strong>Navigation</strong> — the rover is entirely autonomous, using the video feed to control its movements.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

        </div>

        <div class="lynra-media">
          <img
            class="lynra-img"
            src="/images/portfolio/lynra.png"
            alt="Photo collage of the Lynra team and their tree-injecting rover at Dogpatch Labs"
            width="1800"
            height="570"
            loading="lazy"
          />
        </div>

      </div>

    </section>
  </main>
  <SiteFooter />
</BaseLayout>

<script>
  window.addEventListener('load', () => {
    const box = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>('.desc-col > .project-box');
    const frames = document.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>('.demo-frame');
    if (box && frames.length) {
      const h = `${box.getBoundingClientRect().height * 2}px`;
      frames.forEach((frame) => { frame.style.height = h; });
    }
  });
</script>

<style>
  /* Dark mode (default — no data-theme attribute) */
  :global(body) {
    background-image: url('/images/portfolio/bg-dark.svg');
    background-repeat: repeat;
    background-size: calc(100% / 6) auto;
    background-color: #000000;
  }

  /* Light mode */
  :global([data-theme="light"] body) {
    background-image: url('/images/portfolio/bg.svg');
    background-size: calc(100% / 6) auto;
    background-color: #ffffff;
  }

  /* Float the header over the grid — no white bar, no space taken in flow */
  :global(.site-header) {
    position: fixed;
    top: 0;
    left: 0;
    background-color: transparent !important;
    z-index: 100;
  }

  /* ── Layout ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  .portfolio-main {
    min-height: 100svh;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    padding-bottom: var(--space-16);
  }

  .portfolio-title {
    font-family: 'Press Start 2P', cursive;
    font-size: calc(var(--text-2xl) * 1.5);
    font-weight: 400;
    color: #ffe4c4;
    text-align: center;
    margin-top: var(--space-16);
    -webkit-text-stroke: 2px #000000;
    paint-order: stroke fill;
  }

  /* ── Project section ───────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  .project-section {
    width: 100%;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-8);
    margin-top: 20vh;
  }

  .project-heading {
    font-family: 'Press Start 2P', cursive;
    font-size: calc(var(--text-2xl) * 1.5);
    font-weight: 400;
    color: #f699cd;
    text-align: center;
    -webkit-text-stroke: 2px #000000;
    paint-order: stroke fill;
  }

  /* ── Text boxes ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  .project-box {
    background-color: #FF69B4;
    padding: var(--space-6);
    max-width: 600px;
    line-height: 1.8;
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: #ffffff;
  }

  /* Light mode: black text, lighter box colour */
  :global([data-theme="light"]) .project-box {
    color: #000000;
    background-color: #f699cd;
  }

  /* ── Description + demo row ────────────────────────────────────────── */

  .project-row {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-8);
    padding: 0 var(--space-6);
    align-items: flex-start;
    width: 100%;
  }

  /* Left column holds the description; also the positioning context for the
     floated demo-explanation box below it. */
  .desc-col {
    flex: 1;
    max-width: 600px;
    position: relative;
  }

  .desc-col > .project-box {
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .demo-wrapper {
    flex: 1;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: flex-start;
  }

  .demo-frame {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 600px;
    height: 300px; /* set to 2× text box height by script below */
    min-height: 300px;
    border: none;
  }

  /* Show the demo that matches the active theme — dark is the default. */
  .demo-frame--light {
    display: none;
  }

  :global([data-theme="light"]) .demo-frame--dark {
    display: none;
  }

  :global([data-theme="light"]) .demo-frame--light {
    display: block;
  }

  .project-box--left {
    align-self: flex-start;
    margin-left: var(--space-6);
  }

  .project-box--right {
    align-self: flex-end;
    margin-right: var(--space-6);
  }

  /* Floats into the empty pocket directly below the description, so it never
     adds height to the column or pushes the "How does it do this?" box down.
     Narrower + out of flow ⇒ a taller, more square/portrait rectangle.
     left = 48px on top of the row's 24px edge padding ⇒ 72px from the edge,
     the same alignment it had before. */
  .project-box--indent {
    position: absolute;
    top: calc(100% + 200px);
    left: calc(var(--space-6) * 2);
    width: 320px;
    max-width: 100%;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* Decorative arrow floated into the empty gap between the box above and the
     demo. Absolutely positioned ⇒ it occupies no layout space and moves nothing.
     Biased toward the right of the gap (nearer the demo it points at). */
  .demo-arrow {
    position: absolute;
    top: calc(100% + 90px);
    left: 384px;
    width: 230px;
    height: auto;
    pointer-events: none;
  }

  /* ── "How does it do this?" box internals ──────────────────────────── */

  .how-title {
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .how-list {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    padding: 0;
  }

  .how-list li {
    padding-left: var(--space-4);
    border-left: 3px solid currentColor;
  }

  /* ── SSH project: images (left) beside two stacked text boxes (right) ── */

  .ssh-row {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-8);
    padding: 0 var(--space-6);
    align-items: flex-start;
    width: 100%;
  }

  .ssh-images {
    flex: 1;
    min-width: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: calc(var(--space-6) * 2.5);
  }

  .ssh-img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 640px;
    height: auto;
  }

  /* Nudge the first (attack/defense) diagram lower — ~2.5× the image gap. */
  .ssh-img--attack {
    margin-top: calc(var(--space-6) * 2.5);
  }

  /* Show the image matching the active theme — dark is the default. */
  .ssh-img--light {
    display: none;
  }

  :global([data-theme="light"]) .ssh-img--dark {
    display: none;
  }

  :global([data-theme="light"]) .ssh-img--light {
    display: block;
  }

  /* Right-hand column: the two pink text boxes, stacked one below the other. */
  .ssh-text {
    flex: 1;
    min-width: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-8);
  }

  .ssh-text .project-box {
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* ── Lynra: text (left) beside collage image (right) ───────────────── */

  .lynra-row {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-8);
    padding: 0 var(--space-6);
    align-items: flex-start;
    width: 100%;
  }

  /* Left column: the two pink text boxes, stacked. */
  .lynra-text {
    flex: 1;
    min-width: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-8);
  }

  .lynra-text .project-box {
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* Right column: the wide collage, vertically centred beside the text. */
  .lynra-media {
    flex: 1;
    min-width: 0;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
  }

  .lynra-img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 700px;
    height: auto;
  }

  /* ── Desktop ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .portfolio-title {
      font-size: calc(var(--text-3xl) * 1.5);
    }

    .project-heading {
      font-size: calc(var(--text-3xl) * 1.5);
    }

    .project-box--left {
      margin-left: var(--space-10);
    }

    .project-box--right {
      margin-right: var(--space-10);
    }
  }
</style>
